You’re right. I can see exactly what I changed, and the issue is that I replaced the old root page with a very minimal new landing.

At `/` I now serve this new public shell:

```1:126:relocation_jobs/static/public.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  ...
  <title>Relocation Jobs | Visa-friendly software roles abroad</title>
  ...
</head>
<body>
  <div class="site-shell">
    <header class="site-header">
      ...
      <nav class="site-nav">
        <a href="#preview">Preview</a>
        <a href="#how">How it works</a>
        <a class="button button-ghost" href="/app">Sign in</a>
      </nav>
    </header>

    <main>
      <section class="hero">
        ...
      </section>
      <section class="stats-strip" ...>
      ...
```

And I moved the old real app shell to `/app`:

```76:94:relocation_jobs/web/server.py
@app.route("/app")
def app_page():
    resp = send_from_directory(STATIC, "index.html")
    resp.headers["Cache-Control"] = "no-store"
    return resp

@app.route("/")
def index():
    resp = send_from_directory(STATIC, "public.html")
    resp.headers["Cache-Control"] = "no-store"
    return resp
```

So what happened is not that the homepage disappeared. I replaced it with a placeholder-style marketing page that is much thinner than your actual product. That was too aggressive and not a good fit for what you expected.

The current public homepage is basically:
- a hero
- a few stats cards
- country coverage
- company preview
- a simple “how it works”

It is styled in a separate lightweight stylesheet:

```1:40:relocation_jobs/static/public.css
:root {
  --bg: #f5f7fb;
  --surface: #ffffff;
  --surface-muted: #eef2ff;
  --border: #dbe3f0;
  --text: #102033;
  --muted: #5b6b80;
  --accent: #3366ff;
  ...
}

body {
  margin: 0;
  font-family: "Inter", system-ui, -apple-system, sans-serif;
  background:
    radial-gradient(circle at top left, rgba(51, 102, 255, 0.14), transparent 28%),
    linear-gradient(180deg, #fbfcff 0%, var(--bg) 100%);
  color: var(--text);
}
```

And the page content is populated only by two new public endpoints:

```77:98:relocation_jobs/static/js/public-home.js
async function loadPublicData() {
  const [overviewRes, previewRes] = await Promise.all([
    fetch("/api/public/overview"),
    fetch("/api/public/preview"),
  ]);

  if (!overviewRes.ok || !previewRes.ok) {
    throw new Error("Failed to load public data");
  }

  const overview = await overviewRes.json();
  const preview = await previewRes.json();
  renderOverview(overview);
  renderPreview(preview);
}
```

So the honest answer is: I changed the home page too much, and I reduced the root experience more than you wanted.

I recommend one of these two fixes:
1. Keep the public homepage idea, but redesign `/` to feel like your real product and preserve much more of the current board UI.
2. Revert the route split so `/` stays the existing app, then add the public landing on a different route like `/preview` or `/public`.

My recommendation is `2` for now, because it avoids breaking your main entry point while still giving you an SEO surface.

If you want, I can fix this immediately by moving the public teaser off `/` and restoring the old homepage to the root.

